  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "40. stood on the stairs—\"What nobler spectacle than that of Paul at this moment! There he stood, bound with two chains, ready to make his defense to the people. The Roman commander sits by, to enforce order by his presence. An enraged populace look up to him from below. Yet in the midst of so many dangers, how self-possessed is he, how tranquil!\" [Chrysostom (or in his name) in Hackett].",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "a great silence—the people awed at the permission given him by the commandant, and seeing him sitting as a listener.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "in the Hebrew tongue—the Syro-Chaldaic, the vernacular tongue of the Palestine Jews since the captivity.   ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
